T1  - East Indians in the United States Virgin Islands
AN  - 1629331913; 201441021
AB  - The following article analyses the arrival, settlement, identity and participation of a small South Asian diasporic minority group, comprising mainly East Indians from India and Trinidad, in the United States Virgin Islands (USVI). It reveals that East Indians do not fit into the general definition of minority groups in the USVI or even in the wider Caribbean. They have neither been singled out openly for differential and unequal treatment nor exposed to constant incidents of discrimination. These East Indians are also not marginalised or socially displaced in the USVI. Instead, they generally are in good financial standing and equipped with industrial and technical skills to dominate the microeconomic sector and influence political decisions. Moreover, East Indians in the USVI tend to embrace a national homeland identity through the reconstruction of significant political events and social and religious practices (Hinduism) of India and Trinidad while engaging in selective assimilation. They have also contributed significantly to the USVI and elsewhere, building an Indian cultural centre, a Hindu temple, establishing departmental stores and giving substantial sums of money to various institutions in need. Nonetheless, they are viewed with much skepticism by 'Native Virgin Islanders' as a group that has arrived recently and has virtually 'taken over' the microeconomic sector on St. Thomas. So far, there have not been any violent confrontations but constitutional efforts are being discussed to place restrictions on recently arrived, influential ethnic groups such as East Indians in the USVI. Adapted from the source document.
